1. ITERATION SEMANTICS
- for...of on a string iterates by Unicode code points (uses the string iterator) and yields strings that represent full code points (including surrogate pairs).
- Classic for index-based loop accesses UTF-16 code units (str[i]) which may be halves of a surrogate pair.

2. CODE UNITS VS CODE POINTS
- str.length returns number of 16-bit code units, not actual Unicode characters.
- For characters outside BMP length counts as 2.

3. ITERATION PRIMITIVES
- for (const ch of str) { } // yields code point strings
- [...str] or Array.from(str) produces an array of code point strings
- String.prototype[@@iterator] yields code point strings

4. SPLITTING AND CONVERSION
- Array.from(str) splits by code point
- String.prototype.normalize() for Unicode normalization (NFC, NFD, NFKC, NFKD)

5. GRAPHEME CLUSTERS
- Visible characters (user-perceived characters) may be multiple code points due to combining marks, ZWJ sequences, emoji modifiers; JavaScript has no built-in grapheme cluster iterator — use Intl.Segmenter or third-party libraries for grapheme-aware operations.

6. PERFORMANCE
- for...of and Array.from incur allocation cost; for performance-sensitive code prefer manual iteration reading codePointAt and advancing by 1 or 2 depending on code point size.

7. SUPPLEMENTARY DETAILS
- Use Intl.Segmenter('en', {granularity: 'grapheme'}) for grapheme clusters support where available.
- When counting or slicing for display use grapheme-aware tooling to avoid splitting user-perceived characters.

8. REFERENCE DETAILS
- Implementation patterns for safe iteration: use for...of or codePointAt with surrogate-skip logic.
- Example surrogate-skip logic (descriptive): if cp > 0xFFFF then i++ to skip low surrogate.

